In this guided exercise, you will apply what you have learned by using a simple Python program containing a Caesar Cipher to encrypt and decrypt a message.

  1. On the remote lab desktop, click the Terminal Emulator icon in the dock to open a new terminal window.
  2. In the terminal window, type python3 caesar.py and press Enter to launch the caesar.py program.
  3. At the prompt, type encrypt and press Enter to go into encrypt mode.

    If you type anything other than encrypt, the program will go into decrypt mode, and you will need to restart.
  4. At the encrypt prompt, type Bring Caesar a Salad! and press Enter.
  5. When asked for the key, type 5 and press Enter.

    You will see your new ciphertext displayed.
  6. Highlight the ciphertext, then right-click the ciphertext and select Copy from the context menu.
  7. In the terminal window, type python3 caesar.py and press Enter to relaunch the caesar.py program.
  8. At the prompt, type decrypt (or anything other than encrypt) and press Enter to go into decrypt mode.
  9. At the terminal prompt, right-click and select Paste from the context menu to paste the ciphertext from Step 5, then press Enter.

  10. When asked Do you have the key?, type y and press Enter.
  11. At the key prompt, type 5 and press Enter to decrypt the cipher text.
    Note: Only letters A-Z are encrypted and decrypted, which is why the exclamation mark appears in both the plaintext and ciphertext. The program also disregards capitalization, which is why all letters in the output are capitalized by default.
  12. In the terminal window, type python3 caesar.py and press Enter to relaunch the caesar.py program.
  13. At the prompt, type decrypt (or anything other than encrypt) and press Enter to go into decrypt mode.
  14. At the decrypt prompt, type SLAAJ AFAAJ and press Enter.
  15. When asked Do you have the key?, type n and press Enter.

    The caesar.py program will try all possible keys and show the resulting plaintext for one. Most will be nonsense, but you should see at least one plausible result. At a very basic level, this is how     cryptanalysis (the process of breaking encrypted messages) works.
